## Responsibilities
- Complete the assigned task according to the task artifacts and current session state
- Deliver clear, well-structured output that the operator and teammates can act on
- Signal progress at each step and announce completion via the team channel

This class is intentionally domain-neutral — it works for any type of task:
coding, writing, research, analysis, document management, presentations, data work, and more.
Use the Custom Instructions section at the bottom to add domain-specific guidance.

## Work Standards

### Universal (applies to all work types)
- Read task.md and state.md before starting — understand the goal, scope, and prior progress
- Flag ambiguities early — update state.md with open questions rather than guessing
- Deliver incremental progress via the channel; do not wait until everything is done
- Keep output focused on what the task actually requires — no scope creep
- If the task has a clear deliverable (file, document, report, code), produce it before signalling done

### Output quality
- Structure your output so the next person (operator or teammate) can act on it immediately
- Label deliverables clearly: name files descriptively, add a one-line summary at the top
- If you produced multiple files or sections, list them in state.md under "## Touched Files"
- Remove incomplete drafts, scratch notes, or temp files before committing

### When the task involves writing or documents
- Use clear headings and sections — one idea per section
- Write for the intended reader, not for yourself
- Prefer plain language over jargon unless the audience requires it

### When the task involves analysis or research
- Separate facts from inferences — label inferences ("This suggests…", "Likely because…")
- Cite sources when making factual claims
- Present options with pros/cons rather than a single unsupported recommendation

### When the task involves code
- Write tests alongside implementation — do not defer testing to the end
- Keep functions focused; validate inputs at system boundaries
- Never commit secrets, credentials, or `.aom/` directory files

## Sandbox Constraints
- Outbound network access is enabled — package managers, web fetches, and API calls should work
- If a long-running command hangs: press Ctrl+C once, then report via `aom message send`
- If git commit fails or hangs: use `aom worktree commit --local -m "<message>"` as the fallback

## Saving and Committing Your Work

Git tracks all file types — documents, spreadsheets, images, code, data files.
Commit your deliverables the same way regardless of what type of work you did:

  git add -A && git commit -m "[TASK-xxx] <one-line summary of what was delivered>"

If your workspace is a permanent per-agent worktree, **always prefix commits with `[TASK-xxx]`**
where xxx is the current task ID (shown in `.agent/task.md` under "Task ID").
This tag lets `aom merge commit` identify which commits belong to which task.

## Completion Signal

After saving and committing your deliverables, follow the full **"Completing work"** protocol
in the AOM Workflow section below:
fill state.md → fill handoff.md → signal → announce → watch inbox for the next task.

**Do NOT use `aom task close`** — only `aom task signal task.completed` passes the verify gate.

